Neuronal migration is a distinctive feature of the development of the
nervous system. The movement of the unicellular organism
is easy to observe under a microscope. Neural migration can occur by
a similar mechanism. The cytoplasm and organelles in it are moved
from the trailing end of the neuron to the leading edge by contractile
Migration of neurons is particularly important in brain development.
Some neurons that are produced in one part of the developing brain
migrate to another part where they nd their nal position. Mature,
functional neurons do not normally move, though their axons and
dendrites can often regrow if damaged.

An immature neuron consists of a cell body with cytoplasm and a
nucleus. An axon is a long narrow outgrowth from the cell body that
carries signals to other neurons. Only one axon develops on each
neuron, but it may be highly branched. Many smaller dendrites that
bring impulses from other neurons to the cell body may also develop.

Axons grow at their tips. In some cases they are relatively short
and make connections between neurons within the central nervous
system, but other neurons develop very long axons which can reach
any part of the body. Despite only being outgrowths of a single cell,
axons can be more than a metre long in humans and many metres

nervous system. Regrowth rates can be as rapid as ve millimetres
